    <fr:title text="Application of rule induction › "><fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0173.xml" title="Application of rule induction" addr="jms-0173" type="local">Application of rule induction</fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:p>We proceed by <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0171.xml" title="Rule induction" addr="jms-0171" type="local">rule induction</fr:link>, letting <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S = {\mathopen {}\left \{u\,\middle \vert \,P(u)\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. In particular, we need only show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closed under</fr:link> each of the <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rules</fr:link>:</html:p>

 <html:ol><html:li>We note that the empty string has the same (zero) number of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> symbols.</html:li>
  <html:li>Adding both an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> to a given string in whatever location preserves the relationship between the number of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> symbols.</html:li>
  <html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> each and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> each, then the <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016J.xml" title="Concatenation of strings" addr="jms-016J" type="local">concatenation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[uv]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m+n]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> each.</html:li></html:ol>

 <html:p>Therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\in \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> and thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star _{\mathcal {R}}\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
